{
  "card_id": "inversion_fvg_inversion",
  "type": "merged_concept",
  "canonical_term": "Inversion (FVG Inversion)",
  "aliases": [
    "FVG Inversion",
    "IFVG",
    "Inversion",
    "Inversion Fair Value Gap",
    "Inversion FVG",
    "Inversion Gap",
    "Inverted Fair Value Gap",
    "inverted fair value gap"
  ],
  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A fair value gap that price closes fully through, causing polarity reversal: a bullish gap becomes resistance, a bearish gap becomes support on retest. It signals a change in order flow earlier than a market structure shift, indicating the prior imbalance has been repriced.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a valid fair value gap (typically a three-candle pattern with no wick overlap between candle 1 and candle 3) on the working time frame.",
    "Confirm price closes fully through the gap in the opposite direction, not just a wick. The close must exceed the gap's extreme (including consequent encroachment).",
    "Mark the former gap zone as the inversion area; expect polarity reversal (bullish gap becomes resistance, bearish gap becomes support) when price returns to retest it.",
    "Do not treat as a standalone pattern; validate only when the inversion forms within a relevant higher-timeframe point of interest (e.g., after a liquidity sweep, at a t-spot or fair value gap, with a draw on liquidity/structural target).",
    "For stronger confirmation, require a narrow wick on the higher-timeframe candle supporting the expansion, and check for SMT divergence with a correlated asset (optional).",
    "When multiple fair value gaps cluster, treat them as a series and require closure through all before considering the inversion valid.",
    "The inversion can occur after consolidation; it does not need to be an immediate retest.",
    "Extremely large candle ranges may serve as a change-in-state-of-delivery substitute when the closure through the inversion is clear.",
    "Look for price to retrace to the inverted gap and show a reaction that respects it as the new support or resistance.",
    "For stronger validation, confirm with a change in state of delivery or displacement on the same or following candle."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "An inversion provides a high-probability entry trigger or confirmation of a change in state of delivery within the fractal model. After price closes through a fair value gap, the inverted zone acts as support/resistance on retest, often following a liquidity sweep and directional draw. Traders enter on the retest or the close-through, with a tight stop beyond the swing point that formed the sweep or wick, targeting at least 2R or the next liquidity pool. The pattern confirms V-shaped reversals and continuation trades across timeframes.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Taking an inversion entry without higher-timeframe alignment: no prior liquidity sweep, no CISD, or no draw on liquidity.",
    "Entering before the higher-timeframe change in state of delivery is confirmed (e.g., 5-minute closure through opposing candles aligning with hourly bias).",
    "Trading an inversion that does not form at a relevant higher-timeframe point of interest (e.g., not part of the t-spot wick).",
    "Forcing a close entry when risk-to-reward to the next short-term high/low does not reach 2R.",
    "Acting on an inversion when price has already traded all the way back to the opposing liquidity target.",
    "Confusing a mere wick or touch of the FVG with a full close-through that creates a valid inversion.",
    "Trading an inversion on a candle with a large wick that does not support expansion.",
    "Entering on the first rejection through a single fair value gap when there is a series of stacked gaps that have not all been closed through.",
    "Trading an IFVG following a consolidation rather than a clean V-shape reversal.",
    "Failing to wait for the next higher time frame candle open when the closing candle is a large opposing run.",
    "Trusting a continuation closure that struggled through the opposing candle series and also wicked a short-term high/low.",
    "Assuming the inversion must happen immediately; it can occur after a period of consolidation.",
    "Treating a wick or partial close (e.g., 50% consequent encroachment) as a full gap closure, leading to false inversion signals.",
    "Acting on the inverted fair value gap without additional confluence such as a change in state of delivery, order block, or broader market structure confirmation.",
    "Delaying entry until a full market structure shift occurs, thereby missing the early opportunity provided by the inversion.",
    "Entering on a weak retest that lacks aggressive displacement or a prior liquidity sweep.",
    "Failing to confirm a full-body close beyond the gap and assuming an inversion has occurred prematurely."
  ],
